http://dbpedia.org/property/desc.value: The Liberty ship foundered  off Luzon Island, Philippines . All 29 crew rescued.
The Liberty ship ran aground on the Ladd Reef , a total loss.
The 53-gross register ton,  fishing vessel was destroyed by fire in Cook Inlet on the south-central coast of Alaska.
The cargo ship collided with   and sank off the Goodwin Sands, English Channel. Twenty-eight of her 33 crew were killed.
The Liberty ship exploded and sank  north of Bermuda  with the loss of all 18 crew.
The 11-gross register ton,  fishing vessel sank in Swanson Harbor  in Southeast Alaska.
The auxiliary patrol boat was sunk in the Cardenas Bay by a Cuban Exile operated boat.
The fishing trawler sank in a collision with a Soviet Navy submarine. Sixteen of her crew were detained.
The 7-gross register ton,  motor passenger vessel was destroyed by fire at Chignik, Alaska.
The 38-gross register ton  barge sank in the Gulf of Alaska off Cape Saint Elias, Alaska.
The cargo ship collided with   and sank in the Baltic Sea south east of the Gedser Lightship, off the east coast of Denmark. All crew took to the lifeboats and were rescued by  .
The decommissioned  was sunk as a target in the Pacific Ocean off San Diego, California, by the submarine  .
The lifeboat foundered in the 'Seaham Lifeboat Disaster' with the loss of eight men and one boy .
The 71-gross register ton,  fishing vessel was destroyed by fire near Pleasant Island in the Icy Strait in Southeast Alaska.
The fleet support tanker ran aground south of Hartland Point, Devon, England, and was wrecked. All seven crew rescued by breeches buoy.
The 10-gross register ton motor vessel sank near Turnabout Island  in Frederick Sound in the Alexander Archipelago in Southeast Alaska.
The Thames barge ran aground off Walton-on-the-Naze, Essex in a storm.
The coaster capsized and sank  south east of the Owers Lightvessel, off Selsey Bill, Sussex. All nine crew rescued by  .
The 14-gross register ton,  fishing vessel sank at Chilkat , Alaska.
The cargo ship ran aground in the Black Sea. Refloated after nine days.
The coaster ran aground at Canna, Scotland in a storm.
The submarine was destroyed at Ekaterininsky by an explosion. The submarine   was damaged by the explosion. A total of 132 people killed.
The decommissioned  was sunk as a target.
The Liberty ship ran aground near Halifax, Nova Scotia, Canada.

The cargo ship Palmyra collided with the tanker British Mariner  west of Ouessant, Finistère, France and sank. British Mariner was consequently declared a constructive total loss and was scrapped in May 1962.
The 9-gross register ton,  fishing vessel was destroyed by fire on the west side of Renard Island  approximately  from Seward, Alaska.
Battle of Arafura Sea: The TNC 45/Adjak-class motor torpedo boat was sunk in the Arafura Sea by   off western New Guinea. Three crewmen were killed with the survivors rescued by Evertsen.
The coaster developed a severe list  of Bermuda and was abandoned. Crew rescued after nine days by  . East Star was taken in tow by  .
The coaster collided with   and was beached on a sandbank off Kings Lynn, Norfolk. Later refloated and reached port.
The Liberty ship ran aground on the Banc les Quenocs, off Calais, France, and broke in two, a total loss.
The motor vessel sank at Angoon, Alaska.
The barge foundered in the Thames Estuary with the loss of both crew.
The fishing vessel ran aground near Bennal Cove, St. Ives, Cornwall, England. Her entire crew survived. She was refloated and towed to France.
The passenger ship foundered off North Ronaldsay, Orkney Islands.
The steamer foundered off Thassos in the Aegean Sea.
The 143-gross register ton,  pleasure craft was wrecked at Cape Devine  on Korovin Island in Alaska's Shumagin Islands off the south coast of the Alaska Peninsula.

The 23-gross register ton,  fishing vessel sank in "Mallard Bay" on the coast of Alaska. The wreck report does not specify whether the sinking occurred in Mallard Bay  on the coast of Knight Island in Prince William Sound on the south-central coast of Alaska or in Mallard Bay  on the coast of Prince of Wales Island in the Alexander Archipelago in Southeast Alaska.
The passenger ship ran aground off the Vikna Islands, refloated then sank with the loss of 33 of the 79 passengers and crew.
The cargo ship caught fire in the North Sea  northwest of Den Helder, Netherlands. Fire extinguished and ship towed to IJmuiden.
The Liberty ship ran aground at Grand Cayman Island and broke in two, a total loss.
The coaster sprang a leak and sank  off the west coast of Denmark.
The coaster ran aground off Tripoli, Lebanon. All nine crew rescued by a Royal Air Force helicopter. Aghios Nicolaus was later refloated.
The ferry caught fire on a voyage between Newhaven, Sussex, United Kingdom and Dieppe. Escorted into Dieppe at reduced speed.

The ship was attacked and sunk by a Guatemalan Air Force aircraft after firing on the aircraft when ordered to identify herself. Guatemalan President Miguel Ydígoras Fuentes claimed the ship was running arms to Guatemala.
The cargo ship ran aground in the Elbe at Cuxhaven, West Germany.
The bulk carrier ran aground off To-shima, Tokyo and was severely damaged. She was on a voyage from Kobe, Japan to Los Angeles, California, United States. Consequently scrapped.
The 34-gross register ton,  fishing vessel was destroyed by fire at Homer, Alaska.
The 150-gross register ton,  fishing vessel sank in the Bering Sea approximately  north of Seguam Island in the Aleutian Islands.
The 8-gross register ton,  fishing vessel sank at Juneau, Alaska.
The 8-gross register ton,  fishing vessel was wrecked near Ivanof Bay, Alaska.
The Liberty ship ran aground at the mouth of the Elbe and broke in two. A total loss.
The cargo ship was severely damaged when   broke free from her mooring and was driven onto the smaller ship.
The cargo ship collided with   off Hong Kong.
The motor vessel ran aground at Ponta Barra da Falsa, Mozambique, a total loss.
The cargo ship collided with   and sank in the English Channel off Dover, Kent. All 35 crew saved.
The decommissioned  was sunk as a torpedo target off San Clemente Island, California, by the submarines  and  .
The Liberty ship was wrecked on the north coast of the Soviet Union .
The cargo ship collided with   and sank  south of the Nab Tower off the Isle of Wight, United Kingdom.
The 650-gross register ton,  barge sank in the Gulf of Alaska near Chirikof Island.
The cargo ship ran aground at Wakayama, Japan. Later refloated and returned to service.
The Baekdusan-class submarine chaser was sunk in a typhoon in the Pacific Ocean at Guam. She later was raised and was scrapped in 1964.
The Liberty ship foundered off the Pescadores Islands .
The tanker ran aground at Porthcawl, Glamorgan.
Vietnam War: Battle of Quang Khe: The junk was shelled, rammed, and sunk by   off the navy base at Quang Khe, North Vietnam.
The trawler struck a mine and sank off the Netherlands with the loss of all but one of her fourteen crew.

Vietnam War: Battle of Quang Khe: The Type 55A gunboat was sunk with limpet mines at the navy base at Quang Khe, North Vietnam, by South Vietnamese commandos. She was raised, repaired, returned to service.
The Liberty ship ran aground on the Serrana Bank, in the Gulf of Mexico. She was later refloated and towed to New Orleans, Louisiana, where she was declared a constructive total loss.
The tanker ran aground off the mouth of the Gironde, France and was abandoned.
The cargo ship was driven ashore.
The ocean liner ran aground off Cannes, France.
The Owasco-class cutter ran aground on Tripod Reef at the entrance to Pearl Harbor, Hawaii. She was refloated with the assistance of United States Navy tugs within a few days.
The 12-gross register ton,  fishing vessel was destroyed by fire at Sand Point, Alaska.
The coaster ran aground off the Hook of Holland, Netherlands.
A storm destroyed the 171-gross register ton,  motor vessel at the mouth of the Kaliakh River  on the south-central coast of Alaska.
The coaster ran aground at St Alban's Head, Swanage Dorset.
The 119-gross register ton,  tug sank in the Gulf of Alaska.
The Liberty ship was scuttled off the coast of Canada.
The 7-gross register ton,  fishing vessel was wrecked at Thomas Basin in Ketchikan, Alaska.

The fishing vessel ran aground at Land's End, Cornwall, United Kingdom and capsized. Eight of the twenty crew were rescued by helicopter or breeches buoy. Sergeant Eric Smith of 22 Squadron, Royal Air Force was awarded a George Medal for his actions in the rescue.
The 24-gross register ton,  fishing vessel sank west of Karluk Reef  in Prince William Sound off the coast of Alaska.
The cargo ship collided with   and sank  south of Beachy Head, Sussex, United Kingdom. All 32 crew rescued by Jalazad.
The 7-gross register ton,  fishing vessel was destroyed by fire in Cook Inlet at the mouth of the Kasilof River on the south-central coast of Alaska.
The 19-gross register ton  motor vessel was destroyed by fire at Craig, Alaska.

During a voyage from New York City to Northport, Long Island, New York, the  or  , 164-gross register ton tug sank in   of water in Long Island Sound at  — a location described both as off Oyster Bay, Long Island, and as off the entrance to the harbor at Huntington, New York — during a blizzard with the loss of all nine crew.
The 12-gross register ton,  fishing vessel sank near Makushin Bay  on the coast of Unalaska Island in the Aleutian Islands.
The 7-gross register ton,  fishing vessel was destroyed by fire at Larsen Bay, Alaska.
The schooner was spotted, strafed and set afire near Fakfak by a Royal Netherlands Navy Lockheed P-2 Neptune aircraft.
The 84-gross register ton,  barge sank off Ocean Cape  on the south-central coast of Alaska.
The Liberty ship caught fire at Beirut, Lebanon. She was declared a constructive total loss.
The decommissioned  was sunk as a target in the Atlantic Ocean  south of Cape Henry, Virginia.
The 115-gross register ton,  fishing vessel struck a reef and sank in Unga Strait  off the south coast of the Alaska Peninsula.
The 9-gross register ton,  fishing vessel sank in Alitak Bay  on the coast of Kodiak Island.
The Type C2-F cargo ship ran aground on Santa Rosa Island, California.
The pirate radio ship was driven ashore in a storm. She had got into difficulties off Zeebrugge and an attempt was made to tow her to Vlissingen, Netherlands but she broke her tow.
The cargo liner ran aground at the mouth of the River Tees. Refloated the next day.
The cargo ship ran aground off Karpathos, Greece. Her crew were rescued. She was declared a constructive total loss.
On voyage from Alderney to Guernsey with a cargo of gravel, was wrecked on rocks, off Guernsey.
The 8-gross register ton,  fishing vessel sank in Kasaan Bay  in Southeast Alaska.
The cargo liner ran aground off Vatoa Island, Fiji. All passengers and crew rescued after three days.
The coaster ran aground south of Berwick upon Tweed, Northumberland.
The tug foundered with the loss of all 30 crew.
The 43-gross register ton,  motor cargo vessel was lost after colliding with the motor vessel Mutual  in Clarence Strait in the Alexander Archipelago in Southeast Alaska.
The cargo ship sank off the Netherlands with the loss of all but one of her 24 crew.
The cargo ship ran aground in the North Sea off Goeree-Overflakkee, South Holland, Netherlands . She was refloated but deemed uneconomic to repair and was scrapped in April 1962.
The coaster collided with  in Bremen Harbour and sank. All 12 crew rescued.
Typhoon Wanda: The Liberty ship was driven ashore at Hong Kong. Declared a constructive total loss, she was scrapped in situ.
The Liberty ship ran aground on a reef in the Red Sea . Beached and abandoned, she was declared a constructive total loss.
The cargo ship ran aground at Jeddah, Saudi Arabia. Refloated but declared a constructive total loss and consequently scrapped in July.
The cargo ship caught fire at Marseille, Bouches-du-Rhône, France. The fire was extinguished two days later but she was declared a constructive total loss. Scrapped in August 1962.
The cargo ship ran aground in the West Scheldt, Belgium.
The tug capsized and sank at Hull, Yorkshire with the loss of three of her five crew.
Chinese Civil War: The infiltration ship was shelled and sunk by  and  . 23 crewmen killed, 6 crewmen taken as prisoners of war.
Chinese Civil War: The sailboat was shelled and sunk by  and  .

Chinese Civil War: The infiltration ship was shelled and sunk by ,  and  . 26 crewmen were taken as prisoners of war.
The cargo ship ran aground near Jeddah, a total loss.
The decommissioned  was sunk as a target off the Tendra Spit.
The  freighter sank  northeast of Funchal, en route from Detroit to Calcutta.
The schooner-rigged steamship struck ice and sank north of Labrador, Canada.
The speed boat was shelled and sunk by   off Fakfak.
The cargo ship hit a breakwater at Naples, Italy, and sank.
Hurricane Daisy: The sealer, a converted minesweeper, was driven ashore and wrecked at New Harbour, Nova Scotia.
The Liberty ship ran aground off Tallinn, Soviet Union. She was refloated but declared a constructive total loss.

The vessel ran aground on the Minerva Reef. Crew lived in the wreck of a Japanese vessel, wrecked two years earlier, for seven weeks before making a raft and some of them sailed to Fiji. Five crew died before rescue came.
